“The Storm”, newly minted and available on @superrare.co 

“The Storm” depicts a colorful, dilapidated house in the wind swept desert. Floating overhead, an ominous storm cloud recently saturated the ground with life giving rain. Far above, the clouds part to reveal bright stars in the clear night sky.

This work caps my first two years in the NFT space! It’s been quite the fast paced rollercoaster and I’ve immensely enjoyed creating and collecting! Digital work has become a natural part of my art making along with physical paintings. 

“The Storm” is one of only a handful of NFTs I plan to mint this year. My work is purposely scarce- my path in NFTs is quality over quantity. Thank you to my awesome collectors who respect how I create! 

Thanks for checking out “The Storm”! Link in profile.
🌩💎🌩

Intro vid! Some basic info on who I am and what I do. I always find it tough to simplify things down to a few seconds, I’m 48, there’s a lot to my story! This is part 1 ⚡️

Intro vid part 2- a brief history of what I’ve done in the arts. When I say brief I mean it! I squeezed several decades of exhibits, projects, murals, talks and life events into a minute! Fun looking back and finding images for this!  More vids coming- why do I create art? What inspires me? What’s my process? Thanks for watching all! ⚡️ @maxxer242 @rccart @artcenteredu @newimageart @jenyso @riversideartmuseum @kpprojectsgallery

Intro vid 3- What inspired me? Growing up I liked to draw but I REALLY got into art through skateboarding and graffiti. Both had a very diverse and thriving subculture, both were extremely frowned upon, often illegal and both were forms of expression that gave us a voice where we had none.

Ran out of time to chat about other influences/inspirations but I’m having fun with these short clips, more coming next week!
* Yes that is sweat, warehouse section of my studio is 98º 

@artforum @maxxer242 @hextgo @stevendailyart @rg74 @richard_munoz255 @iamdulokshaman

Intro vid part 4- What ELSE inspires me visually? Dreams, the natural world of plants, animals and landscape, other amazing artists and of course- I forgot to mention it- but sci fi and fantasy! Star Wars, Robotech/Macross, LotR... I was lucky to have so many amazing movies, cartoons, video games and toys growing up. Sci fi, world building and pondering what the future holds is still a part of my art!

Still having fun with these short clips,. ‘What my work is about’ is coming next…
Late night paint sesh 🌝

Intro vid part 5- ‘What is my work about?’ That was a very hard question to answer in 90 seconds and I left out quite a bit! I consider myself having explored fine art since 1993, so that’s 30 years or painting. My concerns have shifted as I’ve aged and topics have been all over the place. Early on it was politics and social injustice, later it was man vs. nature topics, still later I was looking for answers to the big picture- why do we exist? What happens when we die? I’ve always been interested in how things we do today (wars, environment, technology, culture) affect the future and that’s one of the things I’m exploring now.

And… truth be told, I don’t always know what my work is about. I fully think that is OK for artists to not know 100%. Sometimes I’m just playing and experimenting visually, sometimes there’s a serious topic/specific goal. Usually I’m working towards something in between- the imagery has meaning, I know what the piece is about (and have my own symbolism), but I also want to create something fun and beautiful to look at.

My next vid will dive into my upcoming show “Sadlands” at KP Projects opening September 9th. Thanks for watching!
🦋💀🦋
@robbieconal @mear_one @kpprojectsgallery

Intro vid part 6- ‘How do I create?’ Since I’ve been working on my ’Sadlands’ exhibit I wanted to show some of my studio practice. As usual, a 90 second video over simplifies this!

For a body of work, I spend weeks and months planning. What am I trying to say with my art? What themes do I want to work with? I take a long time to plan and think and draw, each piece should somehow have a place in the concept of the show.

I use the grid method to transfer drawings onto panels. Shout out to Chet for building these! I leave room for chaos and accidents as I work. I never feel tied down to a specific sketch and often change design elements as I go. This is why ‘m using acrylics rather than oils.

In the video I say I’m just a painter and I don’t have any tricks. That’s not entirely true. You pick up some tricks and techniques over the decades :) I pass some of these down if you take my Painting class at RCC.

Varnishing is always a little scary, but it adds so much depth! For these paintings I used Gamvar as the varnish. This is my first time using it- so far so good!

My next vid will dive into my upcoming show “Sadlands” at KP Projects opening September 9th. Thanks for watching!
🦋💀🦋
@gamblincolors @trekell_art_supplies @kpprojectsgallery

My solo exhibition “Sadlands” opens September 9 at KP Projects, Los Angeles.

I started planning works for this exhibit several years ago and completed the paintings over the last 9 months. This is my first proper solo show since before the pandemic. Earlier this year I moved to a new studio which opened up the possibilities for this exhibit and future projects. 

“Sadlands" is my exploration of landscape painting and world building. This new body of work features my ideas for art installations that could one day exist in a future Southern California landscape. “Sadlands” pulls inspiration from science fiction views of dystopian futures, L.A.’s natural landscape and invasive plant and animals, historical sites and themes of man vs. nature. Each work in the show relates to a real world location in Southern California. 

"Sadlands" opening reception is Saturday September 9, 2023 6-9pm. The exhibit runs 9/9 to 9/30. Interested collectors who would like to preview the work should email: info *at* kpprojects. net

Intro vid part 7- What is Sadlands all about? Sadlands is my exhibit that opens in a few days. It is first and foremost an exploration of landscape painting, in particular the scenery of a future Southern California. But it’s also an exploration into world building, future visions and day dreams. I’m looking into the future while referencing the area’s past and present, with a heavy influence of science fiction and fantasy. And I love where we live and I love maps! There’s more to it, but I’ll let the viewer make some discoveries. 

Join us at the opening- Saturday evening, Sep. 9th from 6-9pm.

I've put out very little this year in the way of prints and pins, I guess it was a busy year for me!! Today we change that, with "The Portal", a hand embellished, timed edition print and "Best Friends" a smaller edition of only 50. We also have an addition to Series 5 pins, the three "Night Owls". All arriving at 10am PST today. Thanks for looking! Link in profile. @stormcloudz

My new works for 2023! 

This has been a notable year for the Sotos, I feel there was an unintentional theme of rebirth/new starts: Jennifer regaining strength and running again after breaking her ankle. Shannon starting college and Natalie starting high school- both excelling and making us SO proud! 

And then myself. I took a financial chance on myself, securing a studio space, investing in new materials, tools, tech and created work for my first solo exhibit in many years at KP Projects. 

I created 20 new major works this year- 18 physical paintings and 2 digital NFT works. The most productive I’ve been in years. I hope to keep pushing in 2024. Thank you to everyone who supported me this year (too many to list)!
@kpprojectsgallery @jenyso @kitty.fart @natalieso._
